}}{{About|the TV series|the eponymous fictional space station|Babylon 5 (space station)}}
{{verylong|date=August 2010}}
'''''Babylon 5''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[science fiction on television|science fiction television series]] created, produced and [[#Writing|largely written by]] [[J. Michael Straczynski]]. The show centers on the [[Babylon 5 (space station)|Babylon 5]] [[space station]]: a focal point for politics, diplomacy, and conflict during the years 2257–2262. With its prominent use of planned [[story arc]]s, the series was often described as a &quot;novel for television&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;soaps1&quot;&gt;{{cite web |first=Jo-Ann |last=Parks |title=Soap Opera 'Babylon' - B5 and the Soaps |url=http://www.space.com/sciencefiction/tv/soap_opera_babylon_000317.html |work=SPACE.com |publisher=Imaginova Corp |date=2000-03-17 |accessdate=2009-10-18}}&lt;!-- original cite {{cite web |url=http://www.space.com/sciencefiction/tv/soap_opera_babylon_000317.html |title=Soap Opera 'Babylon' |publisher=Space.com |date=2000-03-17 |accessdate=2006-09-04}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;cnn1&quot;&gt;{{cite news |first=Dennis |last=Michael |title='Babylon 5' prepares for final bow |url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/TV/9811/20/babylon.5/ |work=[[CNN|CNN.com]] |publisher=Cable News Network |date=1998-11-20 |accessdate=2009-10-18}}&lt;!-- Original cite 2 {{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/TV/9811/20/babylon.5/ |title=&quot;Babylon 5&quot; Prepares For Final Bow |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=1998-11-20 |accessdate=2007-08-21}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;

The pilot film premiered on February 22, 1993. The regular series aired from January 26, 1994 and ran for five full seasons. Due to Warner corporate structure and policy concerning syndication in general and syndication of properties produced by the defunct [[Prime Time Entertainment Network|PTEN]] division in particular, the show has been syndicated only briefly and has not appeared on television since 2000. The show spawned six television films and a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] series, ''[[Crusade (TV series)|Crusade]]'', which aired in 1999 and ran for 13 episodes. On July 31, 2007, a [[DVD]] was released containing two short films about selected characters from the series.

== Concept ==
Having worked on a number of television science fiction shows which had regularly gone over budget, creator J. Michael Straczynski concluded that a lack of long-term planning was to blame, and set about looking at ways in which a series could be done responsibly. Taking note of the lessons of mainstream television, which brought stories to a centralised location such as a hospital, police station, or law office, he decided that instead of &quot;[going] in search of new worlds, building them anew each week,&quot; a fixed space station setting would keep costs at a reasonable level. A fan of sagas such as the [[Foundation series|''Foundation'' series]], ''[[Childhood's End]]'', ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', ''[[Dune universe|Dune]]'' and ''[[Lensman series]]'', Straczynski wondered why no one had done a television series with the same epic sweep, and concurrently with the first idea started developing the concept for a vastly-ambitious epic covering massive battles and other universe-changing events. Realizing that both the fixed-locale series and the epic could be done in a single series, he began to sketch the initial outline of what would become ''Babylon 5''.&lt;ref name=&quot;GEnie-1992&quot;&gt;{{cite web&lt;!-- Archive URL date taken from page metadata, main URL date taken is the one used for the entire document --&gt; |first=J. Michael |last=Straczynski |authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski |title=Babylon 5 (GEnie) posts by JMS for April, 1992 |url=http://www.midwinter.com/b5/GEnie/jms92-04 |archiveurl=http://mirrors.ntua.gr/b5/GEnie/jms92-04 |work=[[The Lurker's Guide to Babylon 5]] |publisher=Steven Grimm |date=1992-04 |archivedate = 1994-03-13 |accessdate=2009-10-19 |quote=...I *love* sagas, and B5 will present a chance to tell that kind of saga. ... But this is hardly revelation; the world of SF print has been doing this now ever since the Lensman books. The job now is translating that approach to television...}}&lt;!-- original {{cite web |url=http://mirrors.ntua.gr/b5/GEnie/jms92-04 |title=[[GEnie]] posts by JMS for April, 1992 |accessdate=2006-08-18}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;concept1&quot;&gt;{{cite web &lt;!-- I'm switching this template from cite newsgroup to cite web because cite web gives me more parameters to explain the cite --&gt; |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-12267 |title=Re: ATTN JMS: Why Accelerate t |first=J. Michael |last=Straczynski |authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski |date=1995-01-24 |work=The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive |publisher=Synthetic Worlds |location=orig. from [[AOL]] (Jms at B5) |accessdate=2009-10-20 |quote=For a long time, a lot of people told me to drop it. My agent said, 'Kiddo, you know I love the project, but I think you've got to face reality. It's not going to happen...'}}&lt;!-- original {{cite newsgroup |title=ATTN JMS: Why Accelerate |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1995-01-24 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-12267 |accessdate=2007-10-31}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Quote box |quote=Once I had the locale, I began to populate it with characters, and sketch out directions that might be interesting. I dragged out my notes on religion, philosophy, history, sociology, psychology, science (the ones that didn't make my head explode), and started stitching together a crazy quilt pattern that eventually formed a picture. Once I had that picture in my head, once I knew what the major theme was, the rest fell into place. All at once, I saw the full five year story in a flash, and I frantically began scribbling down notes. |source=—[[J. Michael Straczynski]], 1995&lt;ref name=&quot;concept1&quot;/&gt; |align=left |width=45em |salign=right}}

Straczynski set five goals for ''Babylon 5''. He said that the show &quot;would have to be good science fiction&quot; as well as good television -- &quot;rarely are shows both good [science fiction] ''and'' good TV; there're {{sic}} generally one or the other [emphasis in original].&quot; It would have to do for science fiction television what ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'' had done for [[police drama]]s, by taking an adult approach to the subject. It would have to be reasonably budgeted, and &quot;it would have to look unlike anything ever seen before on TV, presenting individual stories against a much broader canvas.&quot; He further stressed that his approach was &quot;to take [science fiction] seriously, to build characters for grown-ups, to incorporate real science but keep the characters at the center of the story.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;GEnie-1991&quot;&gt;{{cite web&lt;!-- Note: The Google Cache archive for this cite has been removed because it is a dead link. Google Cache is not an archive; it's a cache. --&gt; |first=J. Michael |last=Straczynski |authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski |title=Babylon 5 (GEnie) posts by JMS for November 1991 through Jan, 1992 |url=http://ftp.midwinter.com/b5/GEnie/jms92-01 |work=[[The Lurker's Guide to Babylon 5]] |publisher=Steven Grimm |date=1991-11 |archivedate = 1994-03-13 |archiveurl=http://mirrors.ntua.gr/b5/GEnie/jms92-01 |accessdate=2009-10-20 |quote=For years, at conventions, I have heard fans lament, and even sat in on panels entitled WHY CAN'T THEY GET IT RIGHT?}}&lt;!-- original {{cite web |url=http://ftp.midwinter.com/b5/GEnie/jms92-01 |title=Babylon 5 posts by JMS for November 1991 through Jan, 1992 |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |year=1992 |accessdate=2007-07-19 |archivedate=2007-06-30 |archiveurl=http://216.239.51.104/search?q=cache:s4lsbb_HEiMJ:www.midwinter.com/b5/GEnie/jms92-01+%22It+would+have+to+be+good+TELEVISION%22&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;cd=3&amp;gl=us}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt; Some of the staples of television science fiction were also out of the question (the show would have &quot;no kids or cute robots&quot;).&lt;ref name=&quot;cuterobot1&quot;&gt;{{cite web |first=J. Michael |last=Straczynski |authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski |title=Well, lemme comment on that. One... |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7700 |work=The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive |publisher=Synthetic Worlds &lt;!-- [[GEnie]] --&gt; |location=orig. from [[GEnie]] |date=1991-12-04 |accessdate=2009-10-20 |quote=...using science the way it should be used, not talking down to the audience. That desire has been noted.}}&lt;!-- original {{cite web |title=Well, lemme comment on that. One... |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1991-12-04 |publisher=[[GEnie]] |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7700 |accessdate=2007-04-26}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt; The idea was not to present a perfect utopian future, but one with greed and homelessness; one where characters grow, develop, live, and die; one where not everything was the same at the end of the day's events. Citing [[Mark Twain]] as an influence, Straczynski said he wanted the show to be a mirror to the real world and to covertly teach.&lt;ref name=&quot;GEnie-1992&quot;/&gt;

== Production ==
=== Format ===
Described as a &quot;window on the future&quot; by series production designer John Iacovelli,&lt;ref name=&quot;Iacovelli1&quot;&gt;{{cite video |people=Iacovelli, John (Production Designer) |date=2004-08-17 |title=Babylon 5: The Movie Collection, Disc 5 Extras: &quot;Creating the Future&quot; |url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105946/dvd#B0002B15UQ |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Warner Home Video]]&lt;!-- Note: Current (2009) URL for http://www.warnervideo.com/ (it's a redirect) physical address --&gt; |location=[http://www.wbshop.com/Terms-and-Conditions/TERMS_AND_CONDITIONS,default,pg.html Burbank, CA 91522] |archiveurl=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Babylon_5#Babylon_5_TV_film_releases |archivedate=2009-10-20 |accessdate=2009-10-20 |id={{UPC|085393343729}} |isbn=0-7907-9132-3}}&lt;!-- original cite: Babylon 5: The Movie Collection, disc 5, &quot;Creating the Future&quot;. --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt; the story is set in the [[23rd century]] on a large [[Island Three|O'Neill Colony]] named &quot;Babylon 5&quot;—a five-mile-long, 2.5 million-ton rotating colony designed as a gathering place for the sentient species of the galaxy, in order to foster peace through diplomacy, trade, and cooperation. Instead, acting as a center of political intrigue and conflict, the station becomes the [[linchpin]] of a massive [[interstellar]] war. This is reflected in the opening monologue of each episode, which includes the words &quot;last, best hope for peace&quot; in season one, changing to &quot;last, best hope for victory&quot; by season three.

The series consists of a coherent five-year [[story arc]] taking place over five seasons of 22 episodes each. Unlike most television shows at the time, ''Babylon 5'' was conceived as a &quot;novel for television&quot;, with a defined beginning, middle, and end; in essence, each episode would be a single &quot;chapter&quot; of this &quot;novel&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;JMSyousay1&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-10170 |title=You say, 'New characters and sets... |first=J. Michael |last=Straczynski |authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski |date=1993-01-21 |work=The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive |publisher=Synthetic Worlds |location=orig. from [[GEnie]] |accessdate=2009-10-20 |quote=One final note: B5 has always been conceived as, fundamentally, a five year story, a novel for television, which makes it very different as well.}}&lt;!-- original {{cite web |title=You say, &quot;New characters and sets... |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1993-01-21 |publisher=[[GEnie]] |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-10170 |accessdate=2007-08-21}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt; Many of the tie-in novels, comic books, and short stories were also developed to play a significant [[canon (fiction)|canonical]] part in the overall story.&lt;ref name=&quot;JMS1996&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-11551 |title=Re: ATTN: JMS Books and TV Plot |first=J. Michael |last=Straczynski |authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski |date=1996-04-25 |work=The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive |publisher=Synthetic Worlds |location=orig. from [[AOL]] (Jms at B5) |accessdate=2009-10-24 |quote=My theory is that *in general* the novels and comics tend to be canon, but the details may not always be, mainly because it's virtually impossible to ride herd on every single line of all this the way I do the show.}}&lt;!-- original {{cite newsgroup |title=ATTN: JMS Books and TV Plot |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1996-04-25 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-11551 |accessdate=2007-08-21}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;

The cost of the series totalled an estimated $90 million for 110 episodes.&lt;ref name=&quot;aicn1&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/display.cgi?id=23963 |title=Babylon 5 Returns |author=Merrick |date=2006-07-24 |work=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |publisher=Harry Knowles |location=Austin, TX 78767-1641 |accessdate=2009-10-24 |quote=Anyway, they asked if I wanted to do a feature film but I declined mainly because I can't yet picture structuring a B5 movie as long as [Andreas Katsulas] and [Richard Biggs] insist on staying dead.}}&lt;!-- original {{cite web |title=Babylon 5 Returns |author= |date=2006-07-24 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/display.cgi?id=23963 |publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |accessdate=2007-11-06}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Writing ===
Creator and [[showrunner]] J. Michael Straczynski wrote 92 of the 110 episodes of ''Babylon 5'', including all 44 episodes in the third and fourth seasons;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |publisher=Lurker's Guide to Babylon 5 |title=Writers/Directors list (JMS entry) |url=http://www.midwinter.com/lurk/making/write-direct.html#JMichaelStraczynski |accessdate=2007-11-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; according to Straczynski, a feat never before accomplished in American television.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=I heard that with you writing the entire season |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1996-04-22 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated/msg/d75b9a8e11b19bad?dmode=source |accessdate=2007-11-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; Other writers to have contributed scripts to the show include [[Peter David]], [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Kathryn M. Drennan]], [[Larry DiTillio|Lawrence G. DiTillio]], [[D.C. Fontana]], and [[David Gerrold]]. [[Harlan Ellison]], a creative consultant on the show, received story credits for two episodes.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |publisher=Lurker's Guide to Babylon 5 |title=Writers/Directors list |url=http://www.midwinter.com/lurk/making/write-direct.html#write |accessdate=2007-11-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; Each writer was informed of the over-arching storyline, enabling the show to be produced consistently under-budget. The rules of production were strict; scripts were written six episodes in advance, and changes could not be made once production had started.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://tech.mit.edu/V118/N24/discuss.24n.html |title=Straczynski, Jablokov Discuss Television, The Future |author=Brett Altschul |publisher=[[The Tech (newspaper)|The Tech]] |date=1998-05-05 |accessdate=2007-12-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Though conceived as a whole, it was necessary to adjust the plotline to accommodate external influences. Each of the characters in the series was written with a &quot;trap door&quot; into their background so that, in the event of an actor's unexpected departure from the series, the character could be written out with minimal impact on the storyline.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.midwinter.com/lurk/misc/cc-leave.html |title=JMS on Claudia Christian's departure |accessdate=2006-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the words of Straczynski, &quot;As a writer, doing a long-term story, it'd be dangerous and short-sighted for me to construct the story without trap doors for every single character. ... That was one of the big risks going into a long-term storyline which I considered long in advance;...&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Re: ATTN: JMS Changes in the Story due to Actors |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski|Straczynski, J. Michael]] |date=1996-04-24 |newsgroup = rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated/msg/0276ecd1f0161a28?dmode=source |accessdate=2009-10-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; The character of [[Talia Winters]] was to have undergone a transformation into a [[Psi Corps]] secret agent, having been revealed as a &quot;sleeper,&quot; whose true personality was buried subconsciously, and who acted as a spy, observing the events on the station and the actions of her command staff.&lt;ref&gt;[[Divided Loyalties]]&lt;/ref&gt; When Winters's portrayer [[Andrea Thompson]] left the series, this revelation was used to drop the character from the series.

{{Quote box |quote=First thing I did was to flip out the stand-alones, which traditionally have taken up the first 6 or so episodes of each season; between two years, that's 12 episodes, over half a season right there. Then you would usually get a fair number of additional stand-alones scattered across the course of the season. So figure another 3-4 per season, say 8, that's 20 out of 44. So now you're left with basically 24 episodes to fill out the main arc of the story. |source=—[[J. Michael Straczynski]], 1996&lt;ref name=&quot;writing&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title=From jms re: yr 4/5 |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1996-12-18 |publisher=[[Compuserve]] |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-6929 |accessdate=2007-11-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; |align=right |width=45em |salign=right}}

Ratings for ''Babylon 5'' continued to rise during the show's third season, but going into the fourth season, the impending demise of network [[Prime Time Entertainment Network|PTEN]] left a fifth year in doubt. Unable to get word one way or the other from parent company [[Warner Bros.]], and unwilling to short-change the story and the fans, Straczynski began preparing modifications to the fourth season in order to allow for both eventualities. Straczynski identified three primary plot-threads which would require resolution: the Shadow war, Earth's slide into a dictatorship, and a series of sub-threads which branched off from those. Estimating they would still take around 27 episodes to resolve without having the season feel rushed, the solution came when the [[Turner Network Television|TNT]] network commissioned two ''Babylon 5'' television films. Several hours of material was thus able to be moved into the films, including a three-episode arc which would deal with the background to the [[Earth–Minbari War]], and a sub-thread which would have set up the sequel series, ''Crusade''. Further standalone episodes and plot-threads were dropped from season four, which could be inserted into ''Crusade'', or the fifth season, were it to be given the [[greenlight]].&lt;ref name=&quot;writing&quot;/&gt; The intended series finale, &quot;[[Sleeping in Light]]&quot;, was filmed during season four as a precaution against cancellation. When word came that TNT had picked up ''Babylon 5'', this was moved to the end of season five and replaced with a newly filmed season four finale, &quot;[[The Deconstruction of Falling Stars]]&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=How will this play out |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1997-05-21 |publisher=[[Compuserve]] |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-2847 |accessdate=2007-11-08}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Visuals ===
{{See also|#Mastering problems}}
In anticipation of future [[High-definition television|HDTV]] broadcasts and [[Laserdisc]] releases, rather than the usual [[4:3]] format, the series was shot in [[16:9]], with the image cropped to 4:3 for initial television transmissions.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-9938 |title=We are shooting in 16:9 |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1993-09-22 |publisher= [[GEnie]] |accessdate=2007-08-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''Babylon 5'' also distinguished itself at a time when models and miniature were still standard by becoming one of the first television shows to use computer technology in creating [[visual effects]]. This was achieved using [[Amiga]]-based [[Video Toaster]]s at first, and later [[Pentium compatible processor|Pentium]] and [[DEC Alpha|Alpha]]-based systems.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.midwinter.com/lurk/making/effects.html |title=The Effects |work=The Lurker's Guide To Babylon 5 |publisher=midwinter.com|accessdate=2006-08-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; It also attempted to respect [[Newtonian physics]] in its effects sequences, with particular emphasis on the effects of inertia.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Physics of Babylon 5 |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1993-09-10 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-9785 |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Foundation Imaging]] provided the special effects for the pilot film (for which it won an Emmy) and the first three seasons of the show. After the show's co-executive producer (Douglas Netter) and producer (John Copeland) approached Straczynski with the idea of producing the effects in-house, Straczynski agreed to replace Foundation, for season 4 and 5, once a new team had been established by [[Netter Digital]], and an equal level of quality was assured,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.babylonpodcast.com/tag/jms/ |title=Babylon Podcast #161: Interview with JMS, Part 1 |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=2009-06-16 |publisher= [[Babcast]] |accessdate=2009-11-28}}&lt;/ref&gt; by using similar technology and a number of former Foundation employees.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Sinking into the sand? |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1996-09-11 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-11839 |accessdate=2007-11-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Emmy-winning alien make-up was provided by Optic Nerve Studios.

=== Music and scoring ===
The original pilot film had music composed by [[Stewart Copeland]] of [[The Police]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0106336/fullcredits |title=Full cast and crew for Babylon 5: The Gathering (IMDB) |accessdate=2007-04-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; When the show was picked up as a weekly series, Copeland was unavailable, so [[Christopher Franke]] of [[Tangerine Dream]] was hired.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-13393 |title=JMSNews: The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; Franke was the composer for all five seasons of ''Babylon 5'', all but one of the television films, and the ''Lost Tales'' DVD.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0006081/ |title=Christopher Franke at the IMDB |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; When Straczynski obtained funds to create a new producer's cut of the pilot film, the original Copeland score was replaced with a new score by Franke.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-3556 |title=From JMS on stuff |date=1997-04-11 |publisher=[[Compuserve]] |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; Over thirty soundtrack CDs have been issued featuring Franke's ''Babylon 5'' compositions, including ''The Best of Babylon 5'', released in 2001.&lt;ref name=&quot;syfy1-BB5&quot;&gt;{{Cite web&lt;!-- Note 2009: The orig. URL needs to be changed to &quot;syfy.com&quot; but the site still seems to be re-indexing its articles at this late date. It's not there yet, but I speculate it may be restored in the future. --&gt; |url=http://www.scifi.com/sfw/sound/sfw7964.html |title=The Best of Babylon 5 |first=Jeff |last=Berkwits |date=2002-01-02 |work=Sci Fi Weekly Issue #547 scifi.com (now (2009) syfy.com) |publisher=Sci Fi |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071130025358/http://www.scifi.com/sfw/sound/sfw7964.html |archivedate = 2007-11-30 |accessdate=2009-10-26 |quote=In the course of television history, few individuals have been given the opportunity to shape the overall sound of a science-fiction series as fully as ''Babylon 5'' composer Christopher Franke.}} &lt;!-- original {{cite web |title=The Best of Babylon 5 |author=Jeff Berkwits |publisher=Sci-fi.com |url=http://www.scifi.com/sfw/sound/sfw7964.html |date=2002-01-02 |accessdate=2007-11-05}}{{dead link|date=October 2009}} --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt;

=== The Babylon 5 station ===
{{Main|Babylon 5 (space station)}}
[[File:Babylon5 01.jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Babylon 5 (space station)|Babylon 5]] orbiting [[Epsilon III]]. The station is described as &quot;a combination of building the [[United Nations]] and [[Times Square]] on an intergalactic scale&quot; by actor [[Bruce Boxleitner]].&lt;ref&gt;''The Guide to Babylon 5'', [[Turner Network Television|TNT]], 1997-12-26&lt;/ref&gt;]]
The station is an [[Island Three|O'Neill Cylinder]], five miles long and a half mile to a mile across, rotating to give [[artificial gravity]]. The center is open, and includes fields, [[hydroponics|hydroponic]] gardens, and a transport tube running the station length. The station has independent, interconnected sectors, designed differently to avoid claustrophobia. Living areas accommodate the various alien species, including differing atmospheres and gravity. Human visitors to the alien sectors are shown using breathing equipment and other measures to tolerate the conditions. As the series begins, the station is under construction, with only parts completed, others lending to shadowy bowel areas. On some outer levels, the viewports are in floor panels, giving a view into space beneath the feet.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=There are a number of... |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1992-01-03 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7710 |publisher=[[GEnie]] |accessdate=2007-11-05}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The station is in the [[Epsilon Eridani]] star system, at the [[Trojan points|fifth Lagrangian point]] between the fictional planet [[Epsilon III]] and its moon.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Babylon 5 Universe: The Station|url=http://www.midwinter.com/lurk/universe/station-1.html|accessdate=2009-07-28|author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]]|date=08-10-1995}}&lt;/ref&gt; The station's first three predecessors (the original Babylon station, Babylon 2 and Babylon 3) were sabotaged or accidentally destroyed before their completion. The fourth station, [[Babylon 4]], vanished 24 hours after it became fully operational.&lt;ref name=&quot;january&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title=Since it is now January 1st, time... |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1991-12-31 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7707 |publisher=[[GEnie]] |accessdate=2007-11-05}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Civilizations ===
{{Main|Civilizations in Babylon 5}}
At the beginning of the series, five dominant civilizations are represented. The dominant [[species]] are the [[Human (Babylon 5)|Humans]], [[Minbari]], [[Narn]], [[Centauri (Babylon 5)|Centauri]], and the [[Vorlon]]s. &quot;The [[Shadow (Babylon 5)|Shadows]]&quot; and their various allies are malevolent species who appear later in the series. Several dozen less powerful species from the [[League of Non-Aligned Worlds]] appear, including the [[Drazi]], [[Brakiri]], [[Vree]], [[Civilizations in Babylon 5#Markab|Markab]], and [[pak'ma'ra]].

While the original pilot film featured some [[Extraterrestrial life|aliens]] which were puppets and [[animatronics]], the decision was made early on in the show's production to portray most alien species as [[humanoid]] in appearance. Barring isolated appearances, fully [[Computer-generated imagery|computer-generated]] aliens were discounted as an idea due to the &quot;massive [[rendering (computer graphics)|rendering]] power&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;JMSemotion&quot; /&gt; required. Long-term use of puppets and animatronics was also discounted due to the technological limitations in providing convincing interaction with the human actors (&quot;…if you want any real ''emotion'' from the character, you're going to have to have an actor inside&quot; [emphasis in original]).&lt;ref name=&quot;JMSemotion&quot;&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Alien looking aliens |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1994-09-06 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-14683 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Languages ===
There are three primary languages used on the Babylon 5 station: English, as well as the fictional Centauri and [[Interlac]].&lt;ref name=&quot;trans&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title=Orange County interview |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1996-12-14 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-6901 |publisher=[[Compuserve]] |accessdate=2007-08-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; English is mentioned explicitly as the &quot;human language of commerce,&quot;&lt;ref&gt;[[Objects at Rest]]&lt;/ref&gt; and is the baseline language of the station (written signs appearing in all three languages).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Re: language...English is the basic… |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1992-07-12 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7326 |publisher=[[GEnie]]
 |accessdate=2007-08-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; Other human and alien languages do exist in the ''Babylon 5'' universe, though with the exception of Minbari, hearing them spoken is uncommon; when aliens of the same species are speaking to one another, the words heard are English, though it is presumed they are speaking their native tongue. Only when in the presence of humans can the alien language be heard, to stress that the humans cannot understand what is being said.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Yes, people will go to the bathroom |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1993-11-04 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-9729 |publisher=[[GEnie]] |accessdate=2007-04-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; With the exception of the [[Minbari#Language|Minbari tongue]], few other alien languages are actually heard aloud on a regular basis.

The [[Gaim (Babylon 5)|Gaim]], [[pak'ma'ra]], and Vorlons do not speak directly in English; in the case of the pak'ma'ra, either because they refuse to learn any language other than their own,&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Learning Curve (Babylon 5)|Learning Curve]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; or because they are incapable of making human sounds.&lt;ref name=&quot;trans&quot;/&gt; Members of these races instead make use of real-time translation devices.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Pat: sorry, but you're strictly... |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1994-11-24 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-8462 |publisher=[[GEnie]] |accessdate=2007-08-15}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The principal human characters speak with an American English accent, with the exception of [[Marcus Cole]], who speaks with Jason Carter's natural British English accent. Susan Ivanova, born in [[Russia]], speaks with an American accent, as her character was raised and schooled outside Russia.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Diversity of B5 populace |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1995-12-01 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-12166&amp;query=winters |accessdate=2007-11-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; Her father speaks with a distinct Russian accent, as does her brother. Various other minor human characters speak English with recognizable regional accents. Ambassadors Delenn and Londo Mollari, both alien characters, speak with distinct accents similar to [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]. Delenn speaks with actress [[Mira Furlan]]'s normal [[Croatian language|Croatian]] accent; most other Minbari have native-speaker accents for English (for example, American English for Lennier, British English for [[Neroon]]). Londo's accent was developed independently by actor Peter Jurasik&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/377/377726p4.html |title=IGN: An Interview with Peter Jurasik |accessdate=2006-09-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; and was imitated by William Forward,&lt;ref name=&quot;Forward1&quot;/&gt; who played Lord Refa. Straczynski has described Londo's accent as being that of the &quot;old school&quot; of the Centauri Imperial Court.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Re:Franklin and Ivanova |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1995-11-12 |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-15929 |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=2007-04-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Narn]]s tend to speak in native-speaker (generally British) accents as well; [[Andreas Katsulas]] adopted a dramatic British accent to portray [[G'Kar]].

== Use of the Internet ==
[[File:Old School.gif|thumb|Original B5 promo logo]]
{{Main|Babylon 5's use of the Internet}}
The show employed Internet marketing to create a buzz among online readers far in advance of the airing of the pilot episode,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Re: Passage through jumpgates (first recorded Usenet post by J. Michael Straczynski) |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski|Straczynski, J. Michael]] |date=1993-07-07 |newsgroup = alt.tv.babylon-5 |id=9307120220.AA08678@relay2.geis.com |url=http://groups.google.com/group/alt.tv.babylon-5/msg/96db83d50eff6a97 |accessdate=2007-03-23}}&lt;/ref&gt; with Straczynski participating in online communities on [[USENET]] (in the [[rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated]] newsgroup), and the [[GEnie]] and [[CompuServe]] systems before the Web came together as it exists today. The station's location, in &quot;grid epsilon&quot; at coordinates of 470/18/22, was a reference to [[GEnie]] (&quot;grid epsilon&quot; = &quot;GE&quot;) and the original forum's address on the system's bulletin boards. Also during this time, [[Warner Bros.]] executive Jim Moloshok created and distributed electronic [[trading cards]] to help advertise the series.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-13730 |title=JMSNews: The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1995, Warner Bros. started the Official ''Babylon 5'' Website on the now defunct [[Pathfinder.com|Pathfinder]] portal. In September 1995, they hired a fan to take over the site and move it to its own domain name, and to oversee the ''Keyword B5'' area on [[AOL|America Online]].

== Broadcast history ==
The pilot film, ''[[Babylon 5: The Gathering|The Gathering]]'', premiered on February 22, 1993, and the regular series initially aired from January 26, 1994 through November 25, 1998,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.midwinter.com/lurk/countries/master/eplist.html |title=Original US airdates at Lurker's Guide |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; first on the short-lived [[Prime Time Entertainment Network]], then on cable network [[Turner Network Television|TNT]]. The show aired every week in the [[United Kingdom]] on [[Channel 4]] without a break; as a result the last four or five episodes of the early seasons were shown in the UK before the US.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.zocalo.nildram.co.uk/UKAirDates.html |title=Original UK airdates |accessdate=2007-08-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; The pilot film debuted in the [[United States]] with strong viewing figures, achieving a 9.7 in the [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen]] national syndication rankings.&lt;ref name=&quot;benson&quot;&gt;{{cite news |title=Warner weblet to 2-night sked |author=Jim Benson |date=1993-05-28 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR107288.html?categoryid=14&amp;cs=1 |publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=2007-12-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; The series proper debuted with a 6.8 rating/10 share. Figures dipped in its second week, and while it posted a solid 5.0 rating/8 share, with an increase in several major markets,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title='Babylon 5' slips a bit in second week |author=Joe Flint |date=1994-02-09 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR118151.html?categoryid=14&amp;cs=1 |publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=2007-12-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; ratings for the first season continued to fall, to a low of 3.4 during [[rerun]]s,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=Sun and hoops sink syndies, rout 'Rush' |author=Jim Benson |date=1994-04-21 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR120389.html?categoryid=14&amp;cs=1 |publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=2007-12-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; and then increasing again when new episodes were broadcast in July.

Ratings continued to remain low-to-middling throughout the first four seasons,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=U's 'Xena' |author=Andrew Hindes |date=1997-02-13 |url=http://www.variety.com/vstory/VR1117435926.html?categoryid=38&amp;cs= |publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=2007-11-06}}&lt;/ref&gt; but ''Babylon 5'' scored well with the [[demographics]] required to attract the leading national sponsors and saved up to $300,000 per episode by shooting off the studio lot,&lt;ref name=&quot;benson&quot;/&gt; therefore remaining profitable for the network.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=Notes from jms |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1995-10-11 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-13613 |accessdate=2007-11-06}}&lt;/ref&gt; The fifth season, shown on cable network TNT, had ratings about 1.0% lower than seasons two through four.

In the [[United Kingdom]], ''Babylon 5'' was one of the better-rated US television shows on Channel 4,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite newsgroup |title=UK C4 ratings |author=[[J. Michael Straczynski]] |date=1995-02-04 |newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-12671&amp;query=ratings%20UK |accessdate=2007-11-06}}&lt;/ref&gt; and achieved high audience [[Appreciation Index]]es, with season 4's &quot;[[Endgame (Babylon 5)|Endgame]]&quot; achieving the rare feat of beating the prime-time soap operas for first position.&lt;ref&gt;''[[TV Zone]]'', January 1998 issue&lt;/ref&gt;

On November 25, 1998, after five seasons and 109 aired episodes, ''Babylon 5'' successfully completed its five year story arc when TNT aired the 110th ([[epilogue]]) episode &quot;[[Sleeping in Light]]&quot;.

== ''Star Trek: Deep Space Nine'' controversy ==
The pilot episode of ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' (''DS9'') aired just weeks before the debut of ''Babylon 5''. ''Babylon 5'' creator J. Michael Straczynski indicated that [[Paramount Television]] was aware of his concept as early as 1989,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-14441 |title=J. Michael Straczynski post |publisher=Jmsnews.com |date=1994-12-07 |accessdate=2010-11-07}}&lt;/ref&gt; when he attempted to sell the show to the studio, and provided them with the series [[Bible (writing)|bible]], pilot script, artwork, lengthy character background histories, and plot synopses for  22 episodes &quot;or so planned episodes taken from the overall course of the planned series&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7864 |title=J. Michael Straczynski commenting on B5's attempted sale to Paramount + B5/DS9 similarities |publisher=Jmsnews.com |date=1996-01-13 |accessdate=2010-11-07}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/ds9season1.php |title=Star Trek: Deep Space Nine: Season One (review) |author=Sylvain, Nicholas, Judge (Retired) |date=2003-04-08 |publisher=DVD Verdict Review}}&lt;/ref&gt; Paramount passed on ''Babylon 5'', but later announced ''Deep Space Nine'' was in development after Warner Bros. announced its plans for ''Babylon 5''. Straczynski has stated on numerous occasions that he thinks Paramount may have used his bible and scripts as the basis for ''DS9''&lt;nowiki&gt;'&lt;/nowiki&gt;s entire main storyarc.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7652 |title=J. Michael Straczynski post from 1992 |publisher=The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive (jms.com) |date=February 4, 1992 |accessdate=2009-10-26}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-3367 |title=J. Michael Straczynski post from 1997 |publisher=The J. Michael Straczynski Message Archive (jms.com) |date=September 15, 1997}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Cast ==
{{Main|List of people involved with Babylon 5}}
{{multicol}}
=== Regular cast ===
* [[Mary Kay Adams]] as [[Na'Toth]] (season two)
* [[Julie Caitlin Brown]] as [[Na'Toth]] (season one, guest in season five)
* [[Richard Biggs]] as [[Stephen Franklin|Dr. Stephen Franklin]]
